	<title>Exercises: Alternating Series</title>
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Which of the following series converges to a number?</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>5 - \tfrac{5}{2} + \tfrac{5}{3} - \tfrac{5}{4} + \cdots + (-1)^{n+1}\tfrac{5}{n} + \cdots</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>c - \tfrac{c}{2} + \tfrac{c}{3} - \tfrac{c}{4} + \cdots + (-1)^{n+1}\tfrac{c}{n} + \cdots</latex>, where <latex>c\in \RNr</latex> is arbitrary.</para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \tfrac{(-1)^n}{\sqrt{n+1}}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \tfrac{(-1)^n }{ 2n + 3 }</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{n+1}{2n+1}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{n+1}{3n+1}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{2n+3}{n^2+2}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{2n+3}{n^2-\pi^2}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{2n^2+3}{5n^2+9}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{2n^k+3}{n^{k+1}+2}</latex>, where <latex>k\in \NNr</latex> satisfies <latex>k\geq 1</latex>.</para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{\sqrt{n+3}}{n+1}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{2^n}{n^{2} + 1}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{n^2}{2^n}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \sin(\tfrac{1}{n})</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \cos(\tfrac{1}{n})</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tan(\tfrac{1}{\sqrt{n}})</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n n!</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{1}{n!}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{n^2}{n!}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{3^n}{n!}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{10^n}{n!}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \tfrac{n^n}{n!}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Let <latex>(a_n)</latex> be a sequence satisfying</para>
			<ol>
				<li><para><latex><![CDATA[ a_0 > a_1 > \cdots > a_n > \cdots > 0 ]]></latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>\lim_{n\to \infty} a_n = 0</latex>.</para></li>
			</ol>
			<para>Then we know that the alternating series <latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n a_n</latex> converges to a number <latex>L</latex>. If <latex>s_n</latex> denotes the <latex>n</latex>-th partial sum of the series, show that</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>\Abs{ L - s_n }\ \leq a_{n+1}</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>for all <latex>n\in \NNr</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
	</exercise>
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Use the previous exercise to estimate</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \dfrac{ (-1)^n }{ n! }</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>with an accuracy of 3 decimal places.</para>
		</problem>
	</exercise>
	
</exercise.pack>